There is a lot of competition in physical therapy practices. Consider it a feasible idea if one of the following are true:
You offer specialty services that are under represented in your town. This may include pediatric, geriatric, pool therapy, joint, sport or other physical therapy specializations. If you research your competition and find it is small or caters to a different niche market, then you will have an advantage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/24/Start-a-Physical-Therapy-Business-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Start-a-Physical-Therapy-Business-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/24/Start-a-Physical-Therapy-Business-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Start-a-Physical-Therapy-Business-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
